<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25184n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25184n">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25184n"> 184(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lesser / means</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In the East, Ceylon was converted during Asoka&apos;s reign, and thence the &ldquo;<mark>lesser means</mark>&rdquo; were preached in Burma and Siam. China is said to have accepted the &ldquo;greater means&rdquo; as early as 65 A.D., and this corrupt sacerdotalism reached Japan from Korea in 552 A.D., and penetrated among the devil-worshippers of Tibet a century later. <small> Claude R. Conder, <a name="CRRM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CRRM"><cite title="source">The Rise of Man</cite></a> (1908) 220</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Right margin  <br>Raphael transcription: <a name="c14125c" href="c14all.htm#c14125c">VI.C.14:125(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
